description:
Completeness check: Round 1-2 missed timing side-channel in hwid validation.

WHAT: generate_eui64() checks if hwid is all-zeros:
```c
bool all_zeros = true;
for (ssize_t i = 0; i < hwid_len; i++) {
    if (hwid[i] != 0) {
        all_zeros = false;
        break;  // <-- Early exit leaks information
    }
}
```

WHY BUG: The early break means the loop time depends on WHERE the first non-zero byte appears. An attacker with precise timing measurements could determine the position of the first non-zero byte in the hardware ID.

IMPACT: Very low. The hwid is read from hardware and not secret, but this pattern could be copied elsewhere for secret data. More importantly, this is in security-sensitive code (identity generation) and sets a poor example.

SECURITY PRINCIPLE: Security-critical code should use constant-time patterns even when the data isn't strictly secret, to prevent accidental information leakage and establish good habits.

FIX: Use constant-time pattern:
```c
uint8_t nonzero = 0;
for (ssize_t i = 0; i < hwid_len; i++) {
    nonzero |= hwid[i];
}
if (nonzero == 0) {
    // all zeros
}
```
